16:
You look wonderful, Adonis! Like a
cute, precious little angel! Or like an
innocent choirboy!
21:
Not sure I'd ever describe Adonis as
a "precious little angel," but okay...
25:
I find overly ostentatious displays
rather lacking in taste—and tedious
to pull off.
30:
However, I suppose I will have to
accept your praise this time. Thank
you.
40:
They've fallen for him, hook, line, and
sinker...
45:
Am I to be the only one with a new
outfit? Won't you change into
something else too, Alk?
50:
Eh... I don't know. I'd just end up in
that kind of situation where one
person is clearly there to make the
other look better.
57:
And how incredibly bold—I didn't
know you thought so highly of
yourself!
61:
Oh, ha-ha. I get it. You know that's
not what I meant. You've got a
twisted sense of humor, you know
that?
64:
Hahaha. I suppose I just pick it up
naturally being around you so much.
70:
Heh. Those two seem to be getting
along well as usual.
75:
A-are they now? They certainly have
an interesting dynamic going on...
Anyway.
79:
Your attention please, everyone! 
On to the main request of the day: 
I'd like you to help with procuring
presents for the orphanage!
86:
We get to pick what presents we
want to give out, right?
89:
That's right. Of course, we should
take the preferences of the children
into consideration as well.
92:
According to surveys carried out
beforehand, many of the children
there are hoping to get some sort of
toy for the holidays.
96:
...Well, that certainly makes sense,
doesn't it.
99:
That stall over there looks like just
what we need. Let's take a look.
106:
Hmm... These toys are a lot more
expensive than I anticipated. It will
be difficult to get one for each and
every child.
111:
Let's do some simple math: The total
budget we got from the guild, minus
the amount we spend on presents,
equals our reward, correct?
114:
Which is to say... The less we spend
on presents, the more that's left over
in the pot for us at the end.
119:
W-we're buying toys for orphans,
Adonis! That's no way to think about
things!
123:
Oh please, Light. You'd do well to
learn to recognize a joke.
127:
O-oh. A joke. I see... I apologize for
doubting you like that.
131:
No need to apologize. Not trusting
someone like me is probably one of
the wisest things you could do.
136:
I-I did not mean to imply you were
an unscrupulous or deceptive
person—
140:
Haha... That too, was a joke, my
friend. Words aren't always meant
to be taken at face value, you know.
150:
So... What should we do? I feel like it
IS possible to just make these from
scratch ourselves, but...
156:
It would be better to buy the highest
quality, most durable toys we have
access to—even if they are
expensive.
160:
Most orphanages aren't nearly
well-funded enough to have proper
toys for children.
162:
If we were to gift them new ones,
only to have them break right
away... Well, that would be quite
devastating for the children, don't
you think?
168:
That's a good point. No skimping on
quality. Hmm... And they should be
safe for the kids to play with, too.
174:
Wood carvings in the shape of
animals. Kids tend to love these.
178:
Yes, and how about we fashion a
hole to pass a string through?
They'd be less likely to lose it if they
could tie it around themselves.
183:
Good idea. We should be able to
figure how to do that without much
issue.
188:
Excuse me, we'd like to buy a bunch
of these wood figures in bulk. How
many do you currently have for sale?
195:
Okay. I'll go get us a tool to poke
holes in these things.
204:
What's with that self-satisfied look
on your face? Have you forgotten
we're dealing with orphans?
208:
Oh, my apologies. It's just... I was
quite concerned about this entire
endeavor. At least initially.
211:
But I'm happy that you seem to be
having a good time here in Starview
Village.
215:
Having a good time? It seems
you've misread the situation.
223:
People in this place are...
frustratingly hard to manipulate.
There are countless other tiresome
matters as well, of course.
226:
However, this is where I've chosen to
be. And I suppose... I don't entirely
dislike it, either.
230:
I see. Well... I suppose not disliking it
is... also a good thing, then.
234: W-wait... Unless that too was a joke?!
239:
Heh. I'll leave that up to your
interpretation.
